And even that tool bench
with the Russian thing

00:50:49.760 --> 00:50:52.830
that I started my slide off
with, or a nautilus shell.

00:50:52.830 --> 00:50:54.890
These are things that are
accessible to everyone.

00:50:54.890 --> 00:50:57.590
I think New York is a
great place to photograph,

00:50:57.590 --> 00:50:59.900
and there are some wonderful
images to be made here.

00:50:59.900 --> 00:51:02.210
In fact, looking at New
York and coming back--

00:51:02.210 --> 00:51:04.400
I grew up here
and have been away

00:51:04.400 --> 00:51:07.520
for maybe a quarter of a
century living other places.

00:51:07.520 --> 00:51:09.170
Coming back here,
it's amazing what

00:51:09.170 --> 00:51:12.570
transformation is happening
all around and everywhere.

00:51:12.570 --> 00:51:14.760
What an incredible
thing to photograph.

00:51:14.760 --> 00:51:16.790
I would just also make
one other comment,

00:51:16.790 --> 00:51:20.890
and that is that I'm a believer
in a concept called resistance.

00:51:20.890 --> 00:51:23.960
That something tries to stop
us from being our creative,

00:51:23.960 --> 00:51:25.340
best selves.

00:51:25.340 --> 00:51:28.520
And what you said is one form--

00:51:28.520 --> 00:51:31.910
it's one I feel too--
one form of resistance.

00:51:31.910 --> 00:51:36.020
One form of resistance for me
is I have to get somewhere.

00:51:36.020 --> 00:51:39.240
I have to take one of my kids
to a doctor, whatever it is.

00:51:39.240 --> 00:51:40.970
And so I don't stop
to make the photo.

00:51:40.970 --> 00:51:42.470
But what you're
saying, it's already

00:51:42.470 --> 00:51:45.534
been done, why should I bother,
is another form of resistance.

00:51:45.534 --> 00:51:48.200
And generally, whenever you feel
that, the best thing you can do

00:51:48.200 --> 00:51:49.910
is say, screw you, resistance.

00:51:49.910 --> 00:51:52.030
I'm going to do it.

00:51:52.030 --> 00:51:53.720
